**Date:** Friday, 08 May 2026
**Organization:** Saeculum Solutions
**Project:** Stasis HRMS
**Intern Name:** ___________
**Supervisor:** ___________

## Work Done

To close out the first week, I spent today consolidating my understanding of the RBAC system by tracing a complete request flow from the frontend through the backend. I picked a specific action — viewing an employee record — and followed every step: the React page calls `can("employees", "view")` before rendering the link, the `ProtectedRoute` wrapper checks the same before allowing navigation, the Axios call includes the Bearer token, the `protect` middleware validates the JWT and fetches `req.user`, and finally `checkPermission("employees", "view")` verifies the user's role has the `view` flag set on the `employees` node of the permission tree.

I then read `RoleModel.js` to understand how roles store permissions. Roles have a `permissions` field of type `Mixed` (a freeform object in Mongoose), which stores the actual permission tree subset granted to that role. The `seedRbac.js` generates these programmatically for system roles, while the `RolesPermissions.js` HR admin page provides a UI for creating custom roles. I noticed that every role mutation is recorded in `RoleAuditLogModel.js`, keeping a tamper-evident history of who changed what permission and when.

In the afternoon, I explored the `navConfig.js` file in the frontend. This is an array of navigation item definitions, each with a `key`, `path`, `label`, `icon` (Tabler Icons class), and `perm` (a `"module:action"` string). The `Navbar.js` component reads this config, checks each item's `perm` using `can()`, and only renders items the user has access to. Groups of items are rendered as collapsible accordions, and the active section auto-expands based on the current route. This dynamic nav means adding a new feature only requires adding an entry in `navConfig.js` and `routeConfig.js` — no changes to `Navbar.js` itself.

I ended the day writing a short summary document for myself mapping the full permission flow, which helped me solidify my understanding. My first week gave me a solid foundation in the project architecture, authentication, RBAC, and the employee data model — all of which underpin every other feature in the system.

## Learning Outcomes
- Traced a complete end-to-end permission check from React UI → Axios → JWT validation → `checkPermission` middleware
- Understood how `RoleModel` stores permission subsets as a `Mixed` Mongoose field
- Learned that `RoleAuditLogModel` maintains a tamper-evident history of all role changes
- Understood `navConfig.js` as the single configuration file driving the entire navigation tree

## Challenges & Solutions
No major blockers today. The first week was primarily exploratory, and having solid documentation in `CLAUDE.md` made orientation much faster than expected.

