## Work Done

Today I was assigned to understand and extend the HR portal's navigation system. I started with `routeConfig.js`, which is an array of route definitions each containing `path`, `component`, `protected`, `permissionPath`, and `action`. This array is consumed by `App.js` which maps each entry to either a `<Route>` (for public routes) or a `<ProtectedRoute>` component (for authenticated routes). Adding a new page requires only adding an entry here — the routing, code-splitting, and permission gating are all handled automatically.

I then studied `navConfig.js` in detail. The nav config is hierarchical — top-level items can be either direct links or accordion groups containing child items. Each item has a `perm` string in the format `"module:action"` which the `Navbar.js` component parses to call `can(module, action)`. If all children of an accordion group fail the permission check, the entire group is hidden — this prevents empty accordion sections appearing in the sidebar for restricted roles.

I made a small contribution today: I added proper `aria-current="page"` attributes to the active nav link in `Navbar.js`. This improves accessibility for screen reader users and also makes the CSS active-state selector more semantic. The change was small but required understanding how React Router's `useLocation()` hook is used to determine the current path and compare it against each nav item's `path` property.

I also read `hooks/usePermission.js` to understand how permission checks work in components that aren't route-level — for example, conditional rendering of buttons inside a page. The `usePermission` hook simply calls `useContext(AuthContext)` and returns the `can` function. The `Can.js` component is a thin wrapper around this hook that renders its children only if the permission check passes — useful for declarative permission gating in JSX without verbose ternary expressions.

## Learning Outcomes
- Understood how `routeConfig.js` drives the entire routing and permission-gating system with a data-driven approach
- Learned the difference between `navConfig.js` (sidebar navigation) and `routeConfig.js` (actual React Router routes)
- Understood the `Can.js` component pattern for declarative permission checks in JSX
- Applied `aria-current` for accessible active state in the navigation

## Challenges & Solutions
Finding where to add the `aria-current` attribute was initially confusing because the active state logic was split across CSS classes and JavaScript comparisons. Tracing the `useLocation()` usage clarified it quickly.

