**Date:** Thursday, 14 May 2026
**Organization:** Saeculum Solutions
**Project:** Stasis HRMS
**Intern Name:** ___________
**Supervisor:** ___________

## Work Done

Today I dived deeper into the RBAC system by examining `RolesPermissions.js` in the HR admin section. This is one of the most complex pages in the HR portal — it allows HR admins to create custom roles, assign granular permissions using a tree of checkboxes, and manage user assignments. The permission tree UI is generated dynamically from the same `permissions.js` config used on the backend, ensuring the frontend tree always reflects the backend's actual permission structure.

I studied how the `RolesPermissions.js` page constructs the permission tree UI. It imports a flattened representation of the permissions config and renders each path as a row with checkboxes for each available action (`view`, `create`, `modify`, `delete`). When a checkbox is toggled, it updates a local state object representing the role's permissions. On save, this object is sent to `PUT /api/rbac/roles/:id` which stores it in the `RoleModel.permissions` Mixed field.

I then read `rbacController.js` in the backend to understand the role creation, update, and deletion flows. The controller has special protection for system roles — roles with `isSystem: true` in the database cannot be deleted or have their name changed. The admin role additionally cannot have its permissions modified at all (it always gets the wildcard `*` set on server start). Every role change goes through `writeAudit()` from `utils/audit.js`, which creates a record in `AuditLogModel` and `RoleAuditLogModel` with the before/after state, the acting user, and a timestamp.

In the afternoon I read `middleware/activeGuard.js` which is the `checkActiveEmployee()` middleware. This middleware is applied to employee-portal routes and checks that the logged-in employee's account is still active in the system — if the employee has been offboarded or their account disabled, all API calls from the employee portal return a 403. This is a defense-in-depth measure: even if a JWT hasn't expired yet, a recently disabled employee cannot access their portal.

## Learning Outcomes
- Understood how the `RolesPermissions.js` page dynamically generates the permission tree UI from the backend's config
- Learned how `writeAudit()` creates immutable audit records for every sensitive change
- Understood the `activeGuard` middleware as a defense-in-depth measure independent of JWT expiry
- Learned that system roles have immutability protections enforced at the controller level

## Challenges & Solutions
The Mixed field type in Mongoose (used for the permissions object) requires calling `.markModified("permissions")` before `.save()` — otherwise Mongoose doesn't detect the change and skips the database update. This was a subtle gotcha I found by reading the Mongoose docs.

