On the last day of my second week, I wrapped up my exploration of the employee management and RBAC modules by reading the `Users.js` and `EmployeeAccounts.js` admin pages. `Users.js` manages the `UserModel` records (login accounts), while `EmployeeAccounts.js` provides a bulk view that links employees to their user accounts. An employee can exist without a user account (if they haven't been given system access yet), but every user account must be linked to an employee.

I also read `adminController.js` which handles user management operations: creating users, resetting passwords, enabling/disabling accounts, and assigning roles. A key detail here is password hashing — passwords are hashed using `bcryptjs` with a salt factor of 10 before being stored. The `resetPassword` handler generates a temporary password, emails it to the user (via `emailUtils.js`), and sets a flag that forces a password change on first login. The `SetPassword.js` frontend page handles the forced password change flow.

I then spent the afternoon doing a code review pass on all the changes I had made during the week. I checked that every component I had touched used the established CSS classes (`.field-input`, `.field-label`, `.btn-primary`, etc.) from the shared design system in `main.css`, verified there were no hardcoded colors, and confirmed that all user-facing strings were in sentence case (per the `STASIS_CONTENT_GUIDE.md` rules). This self-review habit was encouraged by my supervisor as a way to catch style inconsistencies before they accumulate.

I committed all my changes and wrote a brief summary of the two weeks' work for my supervisor. The first two weeks gave me a thorough understanding of the system's foundation — authentication, RBAC, employee data model, and navigation — which I would build on in the weeks ahead as I moved into more domain-specific modules.

