**Date:** Tuesday, 19 May 2026
**Organization:** Saeculum Solutions
**Project:** Stasis HRMS
**Intern Name:** ___________
**Supervisor:** ___________

## Work Done

Continuing from yesterday's study of the attendance engine, today I focused on the punch-in/out system. I read `AttendanceRecordModel.js` which stores one document per employee per day. Each record contains the employee code, the date key (an integer in YYYYMMDD format — a clever choice for efficient range queries), an array of punch events (each with a type of `in` or `out` and a timestamp), and the computed status fields (status, worked minutes, effective productive minutes, late flag, etc.). The YYYYMMDD integer format means range queries like "all records in May 2026" become simple comparisons: `dateKey >= 20260501 && dateKey <= 20260531` — faster and more intuitive than ISO date range queries.

I then read `attendanceController.js`, specifically the `addPunch` handler. When an employee punches in or out, this handler validates the punch type (must alternate — can't punch in twice), appends the punch event to the record's array, and immediately recomputes the status using `computeDayStatus` to give the employee a real-time view of their attendance status. This live recomputation on every punch is a deliberate design choice: HR and the employee can both see the current status throughout the day rather than waiting for the nightly finalization job.

I studied the `PunchWidget.js` component in the employee portal — a prominent card on the Dashboard that shows the current status and has a single "Punch In" / "Punch Out" button. The widget uses a 30-second polling interval to fetch the live stats from `GET /api/emp-portal/attendance/today`, which returns the punch history and a `stats` block computed by `buildLiveStats`. The `stats` block includes remaining target minutes, current break range warnings, late count, and provisional status — giving the employee actionable feedback ("You have been clocked in for 5h 20m. 2h 35m remaining to complete your working day.").

I also looked at `empPortalController.js` which handles all `/api/emp-portal/*` routes. A key design principle here: every handler in this controller only accesses data for the currently authenticated employee (`req.user.emp_code`) — there are no permission checks in these routes because the scope is already scoped to the caller. This keeps the employee portal simple and secure without needing a complex RBAC tree.

## Learning Outcomes
- Understood the YYYYMMDD integer date key pattern for efficient MongoDB range queries
- Learned how punch events are stored as an embedded array and status is recomputed live on each punch
- Understood the `buildLiveStats` function that provides real-time feedback to employees via the PunchWidget
- Learned that `empPortalController.js` is scoped to `req.user.emp_code` — no RBAC needed, security by design

## Challenges & Solutions
I initially wondered why the system uses a YYYYMMDD integer instead of a proper Date field with date-only indexes. The answer is practical: sorting and range-querying integers is marginally faster, and the format is human-readable in raw MongoDB queries during debugging.

