## Work Done

Week four began with implementing the regularization request feature on the employee portal side. I was tasked with building the `Regularization.js` page in `hrms-frontend-employee/src/pages/`. Employees can submit punch correction requests from this page — they select a date, provide their proposed punch times (in/out pairs), and add a reason. The submission goes to `POST /api/regularization/request`.

I started by reading `RegularizationRequestModel.js`. Each regularization request stores the employee code, the date of the punch correction, the original punches (before correction), the proposed punches, the reason text, the submission timestamp, and the approval status (`pending` / `approved` / `rejected`). Approved requests also store who approved them and when, along with any HR note. Rejected requests require a note.

The most important validation rule I had to implement is the `regularizationWindowDays` check — the request can only be submitted for dates within the last N working days (where N comes from the attendance policy). I implemented this in the frontend by fetching the policy and computing the earliest allowed date using the `subtractWorkingDays` equivalent logic in JavaScript. If the selected date is outside the window, the submit button is disabled with a descriptive message: "You can only submit corrections for dates within the last 3 working days."

I also handled the monthly limit: I added a call to fetch the employee's regularization count for the current month before showing the form. If they've hit the limit, I showed a warning banner: "You've used all your regularization slots for this month. Your request will still be accepted but is flagged for HR review." This matches the backend behavior — over-limit requests are accepted but flagged with `overLimit: true` rather than hard-rejected. This soft-cap design was specified in `CLAUDE.md`.

## Learning Outcomes
- Built the employee-side regularization request form end to end
- Implemented client-side `regularizationWindowDays` validation using working-day math
- Understood the soft-cap design for `maxRegularizationsPerMonth` — warn, don't block
- Learned that rejected/cancelled requests don't consume a monthly slot (only approved ones count)

## Challenges & Solutions
Computing the earliest allowed date on the frontend (to disable past dates in the date picker) required implementing the same working-day subtraction logic as the backend's `subtractWorkingDays` utility. I extracted this into a small `subtractWorkingDaysClient(date, n, holidays)` helper function in the component.

