**Date:** Tuesday, 02 June 2026
**Organization:** Saeculum Solutions
**Project:** Stasis HRMS
**Intern Name:** ___________
**Supervisor:** ___________

## Work Done

Today I explored the PDF generation system — one of the most infrastructure-heavy parts of the backend. Stasis HRMS uses `wkhtmltopdf` 0.12.6 for all PDF generation. The decision to use `wkhtmltopdf` instead of Puppeteer/Chromium is deliberate and documented in `CLAUDE.md`: wkhtmltopdf is significantly lighter and faster for server-side PDF generation of structured documents, and it's installed directly in the Docker container via apt, avoiding the 300MB+ Chromium download.

I read `services/document/core/pdfGenerator.js` to understand the generation pipeline. The generator takes an HTML string and calls `wkhtmltopdf` with specific options: `pageSize A4`, zero margins, `printMediaType`, `background`, `UTF-8` encoding. It does NOT set DPI, imageDPI, or minimumFontSize overrides — I learned from `CLAUDE.md` that these overrides were tried previously and caused rendering inconsistencies. The generator returns a Buffer that can be either saved to Drive or sent directly as a file download response.

I studied `services/document/core/pdfLayout.js` which defines the page size constants (A4 width/height in mm, usable area accounting for margins) used by all document builders. Then I read `services/document/core/pdfTemplateBuilder.js` which provides the base HTML shell: it injects the Lexend Google Font, sets baseline CSS (font-family, color, table styles), and wraps the document content in a proper HTML5 structure. Every document builder must call this template wrapper to ensure consistent fonts and base styles.

I traced a complete document generation flow by reading `services/document/builders/payslipBuilder.js`. The builder function takes the employee data and payroll run data, constructs an HTML table with all salary components, and returns an HTML string. The controller in `documentController.js` calls this builder, passes the result to `pdfGenerator.js`, uploads the PDF to Google Drive, and saves a record in `EmployeeDocumentModel.js` with the Drive file ID.

## Learning Outcomes
- Understood the wkhtmltopdf-based PDF pipeline: builder → template wrapper → generator → Drive upload → DB record
- Learned why wkhtmltopdf is used over Puppeteer: lighter, faster, no Chromium required
- Understood `pdfLayout.js` as the single source of truth for page dimension constants
- Learned that the `pdfTemplateBuilder.js` wrapper handles font injection and base CSS for all documents

## Challenges & Solutions
Understanding the margin and dimension math in `pdfLayout.js` required knowing wkhtmltopdf's coordinate system (zero margins means the builder must set its own padding in HTML/CSS). No code blockers today.

