**Supervisor:** ___________

## Work Done

Continuing the email work, today I implemented the WYSIWYG email builder feature — one of the most impactful quality-of-life improvements for non-technical HR staff. The requirement was to add a Visual editing tab (the default) to the existing `EmailManager.js` page so that HR can edit email templates without writing HTML. The constraint was no new npm dependencies — the entire rich-text editor had to be built with browser built-ins.

I created `hrms-frontend/src/components/RichEmailEditor.js` using the `contenteditable` HTML attribute and `document.execCommand` for text formatting. Although `execCommand` is technically deprecated, it remains universally supported in all modern browsers and is the only way to implement a rich-text editor without a library. The toolbar includes: paragraph/heading style selector, bold/italic/underline, ordered/unordered lists, text alignment, link insertion (via `window.prompt`), a color swatch picker, and a "clear formatting" button.

The most technically interesting part was the variable insertion menu. Email templates use `{{variable}}` placeholders (like `{{employeeName}}`, `{{joiningDate}}`). The editor renders a dropdown of available variables from the template's metadata. When a variable is selected, `document.execCommand("insertText", false, "{{variableName}}")` inserts it at the current cursor position in the contenteditable div. This works seamlessly with the rich-text content.

I also had to solve the React state synchronization problem with contenteditable. The standard React controlled-component approach (setting `innerHTML` on each render) causes the cursor to jump to the beginning on every keystroke. I solved this using a `useRef` to the contenteditable element and only syncing `innerHTML` when the value changes externally (template switch) AND the element doesn't have focus — if the user is actively typing, React never touches the DOM.

I wired this into `EmailManager.js`: the page now has three tabs — Visual (default, `RichEmailEditor`), HTML (raw textarea), and Preview (read-only rendered HTML in an iframe). Switching between tabs syncs the content bidirectionally.

## Learning Outcomes
- Built a zero-dependency WYSIWYG rich-text editor using `contenteditable` and `document.execCommand`
- Solved the React + `contenteditable` cursor-jump problem using a ref-based sync strategy
- Implemented the `{{variable}}` insertion menu using `document.execCommand("insertText")`
- Understood the three-tab (Visual/HTML/Preview) editing workflow for non-technical users

## Challenges & Solutions
The cursor-jump problem with `contenteditable` was the hardest challenge of the week. The key insight: only sync `innerHTML` from React state to the DOM when the user is NOT currently editing (i.e., the element doesn't have focus). This required the `document.activeElement !== editorRef.current` guard.

