## Work Done

Today I started on the asset management module. I read through the three asset models: `AssetItemModel.js` (the catalog of asset types — laptops, monitors, chairs, etc.), `AssetUnitModel.js` (specific physical units with serial numbers and current assignment), and `EmployeeAssetModel.js` (the assignment history linking units to employees). This three-model separation cleanly distinguishes between "what kind of asset" (item), "which specific unit" (unit), and "who has it now" (assignment).

I read `assetController.js` to understand the QR code generation feature. Each `AssetUnit` has a unique serial number, and the controller generates an HMAC-SHA256 QR code for each unit using `process.env.ASSET_QR_SECRET`. The QR code encodes both the serial number and a signature (`sig = hmac(serialNumber)`). This same QR code is also used by the Electron tracker agent for device enrollment — scanning the QR proves the device is a company-owned asset without sharing the HMAC secret with the agent.

I studied the asset assignment flow: when HR assigns an asset unit to an employee, the controller updates `AssetUnitModel.assignedToCode` and creates a new `EmployeeAssetModel` record marking the assignment date. When the asset is returned, a return date is added to the assignment record and `assignedToCode` is cleared. This gives a full assignment history for every unit.

I also looked at `PublicAssetDetail.js` — a public page (no authentication) that shows basic asset information when a QR code is scanned by anyone. This is useful for IT support: scanning an asset sticker shows who it's assigned to and when it was assigned, without requiring an HR login. The route is mounted outside the `protect` chain.

I spent the afternoon studying how the asset module would eventually integrate with the tracker agent enrollment flow — something I would work on in detail in week nine.

## Learning Outcomes
- Understood the three-model asset structure: item (catalog) → unit (physical) → assignment (history)
- Learned the HMAC-SHA256 QR code generation pattern and how the same secret is used for tracker agent enrollment
- Understood the `PublicAssetDetail.js` public page for QR-code-based asset lookups
- Traced the assignment/return lifecycle in `assetController.js`

## Challenges & Solutions
Understanding why a separate `EmployeeAssetModel` is needed (rather than just storing current assignment in `AssetUnitModel`) became clear when I thought about history: you need to know every previous assignment, not just the current one. The separate model is the right design.

