## Work Done

Today I studied the onboarding timeline system in depth — the module that tracks and automates the new hire journey from offer acceptance to completion of onboarding steps. I read `onboardingController.js` which is the largest controller file in the backend (~1,000+ lines). It handles the public offer letter response page, the public policy document sign-off page, step completion/reversion by HR, appraisal date computation, and the queueing of all scheduled reminders.

I focused on `computeAppraisalDate(joiningDate)` — the canonical appraisal date computation function. This function implements the rule from `CLAUDE.md`: the appraisal is 1 year from the joining date, snapped to the 1st of a month (joining day ≤ 10 → same month first next year; joining day > 10 → next month first next year), then weekend-shifted. I traced this function and verified it handles edge cases: a joining date of January 5 produces February 1 (next year, same month, but wait — joining day 5 ≤ 10, so same month), and a joining date of January 15 produces March 1 (next year, next month).

I studied `normalizeScheduledDate(isoString)` — a counterpart to `shiftWeekend` but operating on ISO date strings rather than YYYYMMDD integer keys. This is used for "scheduled for" dates stored as full ISO timestamps rather than date keys. The function converts the ISO string to a Date, checks the day of week, and shifts weekends.

I also read the `respondPublicOfferLetter` handler which manages the public offer letter acceptance page (`OfferLetterResponse.js` in the frontend). When an employee clicks the acceptance link in their offer email, they can review the offer, tick acknowledgement checkboxes, and submit their acceptance. The handler updates the employee's onboarding status and queues the first set of reminder events (joining reminder, 1-month meeting, 2-month meeting, 3-month meeting, appraisal reminder).

## Learning Outcomes
- Understood `computeAppraisalDate` — the canonical implementation of the 1-year, 1st-of-month, weekend-shift appraisal rule
- Learned `normalizeScheduledDate` as the ISO string counterpart to `shiftWeekend`
- Traced the `respondPublicOfferLetter` handler and understood all the events queued at offer acceptance
- Understood that all onboarding timeline date computation must route through canonical helpers — no inline re-derivation

## Challenges & Solutions
I initially tried to trace the appraisal date computation by following the `pqUtils/dateKeyUtils.js` path, which uses integer keys. The `onboardingController.js` uses Date objects via `computeAppraisalDate`, while the PQ uses `normalizeAppraisalKey` (integer keys). Both implement the same rule but for different data types — I had to keep them mentally separate.

