**Date:** Monday, 22 June 2026
**Organization:** Saeculum Solutions
**Project:** Stasis HRMS
**Intern Name:** ___________
**Supervisor:** ___________

## Work Done

Week eight began with a major feature: the digital e-signature system. I started with research on legal requirements before writing a single line of code. I studied the Indian Information Technology Act 2000 (IT Act 2000) Section 5 and 10A which gives legal recognition to electronic signatures and contracts. I also reviewed the US Electronic Signatures in Global and National Commerce Act (ESIGN) and the Uniform Electronic Transactions Act (UETA) for reference on what constitutes a legally valid electronic signature.

The key requirements for legal validity are: (1) intent to sign — the signer must affirmatively consent, (2) attribution — the signature must be attributable to the specific person, (3) integrity — the signed document must be tamper-evident, (4) record retention — signatures must be retained for the legally required period (8 years for employment contracts under Indian labor law). I designed the signature system to satisfy all four requirements.

I designed `SignatureRecordModel.js` as an immutable audit model. The schema stores: context (candidate_application/onboarding_offer/onboarding_policy/offboarding_exit), subjectType and subjectId (what was signed), empCode, signerName and signerEmail, consentAccepted flag, consentText (exact text of what was agreed to), documentType, documentVersion, documentHash (SHA-256 of the signed content), signatureImage Drive file ID, ipAddress, userAgent, signedAt, and retentionUntil (+8 years from signature).

To make the model immutable, I added a `pre("save")` hook that blocks all saves on non-new documents, and `pre` hooks on all update/delete operations (`updateOne`, `updateMany`, `findOneAndUpdate`, `replaceOne`, `deleteOne`, `deleteMany`, `findOneAndDelete`, `findOneAndRemove`) that throw an error. This ensures that no signature record can ever be modified or deleted, even by a developer with direct MongoDB access through the application layer.

## Learning Outcomes
- Researched IT Act 2000, ESIGN, and UETA legal requirements for electronic signature validity
- Designed the four pillars of the signature system: intent, attribution, integrity, retention
- Built `SignatureRecordModel.js` as an immutable Mongoose model using pre-hooks to block all mutations
- Understood the 8-year retention requirement and implemented `retentionUntil` as a Date field

## Challenges & Solutions
Making Mongoose models truly immutable required blocking not just `save()` but all the update/delete query methods. Missing even one (e.g., `findOneAndUpdate`) would leave a gap. I systematically listed all Mongoose mutation methods and added hooks for each.

