**Date:** Tuesday, 23 June 2026
**Organization:** Saeculum Solutions
**Project:** Stasis HRMS
**Intern Name:** ___________
**Supervisor:** ___________

## Work Done

Continuing from yesterday's model design, today I implemented `services/signature/signatureService.js`. The `recordSignature(req, opts)` function is the single entry point for creating signature records across all contexts. It accepts all the fields needed to create a `SignatureRecordModel` document and handles two responsibilities: computing server-side fields (IP, user-agent, timestamp) that the client must never control, and uploading the signature image to Google Drive.

For the IP address, I implemented `clientIp(req)` which reads `X-Forwarded-For` header first (since the backend runs behind a Docker reverse proxy and `req.ip` might be `::1`). The backend has `app.set("trust proxy", true)` set in `server.js`, which makes Express correctly interpret the `X-Forwarded-For` header. The signed-at timestamp is always `new Date()` computed on the server — the client's claimed timestamp is ignored.

For document integrity, the function computes `documentHash = crypto.createHash("sha256").update(signedContent).digest("hex")`. The `signedContent` is a JSON string of the document contents (form fields, acknowledgement text, or the full document key). If the signed content ever changes after signature, the hash will no longer match — providing tamper evidence.

For the signature image, if the caller provides an `existingDriveFileId` (used when the image was already uploaded as part of the application flow), the service reuses that file ID. Otherwise, it decodes the base64 data URL to a Buffer and calls `uploadFile()` from `driveService.js` to create a new Drive file in the employee's signatures folder.

I also created `signatureController.js` with a single `listSignatures(req, res)` handler (GET only — no create/update/delete) and wired it into `server.js` as `GET /api/signatures`.

## Learning Outcomes
- Implemented `recordSignature()` as a server-side authority: IP, UA, and timestamp are always server-computed
- Learned the SHA-256 document hash approach for tamper-evident integrity
- Understood the `existingDriveFileId` optimization to avoid double-uploading when images are already in Drive
- Reinforced that `listSignatures` is GET-only — no mutation endpoints exist, by design

## Challenges & Solutions
Decoding a base64 data URL to a Buffer requires stripping the `data:image/png;base64,` prefix before calling `Buffer.from(str, "base64")`. I added a `dataUrlToBuffer(dataUrl)` helper for this parsing.

