**Date:** Wednesday, 24 June 2026
**Organization:** Saeculum Solutions
**Project:** Stasis HRMS
**Intern Name:** ___________
**Supervisor:** ___________

## Work Done

Today I built the frontend signature capture components. I created `SignaturePad.js` — a React component that provides the consent-gated canvas-based signature pad. The component accepts a `consentText` prop (the exact legal text to be agreed to) and an `onChange` callback that fires with `{ accepted, dataUrl, consentText }`.

The consent gate is implemented as a checkbox: the canvas and drawing tools only appear after the user checks the box. This ensures the user has read and explicitly agreed to the consent text before they can draw their signature — satisfying the "intent to sign" legal requirement. Once the checkbox is checked, a 560×170 pixel HTML5 Canvas element appears below it.

I implemented touch and mouse drawing support in the canvas using a single `useEffect` that runs when `accepted` becomes true. The effect adds event listeners for `mousedown`, `mousemove`, `mouseup`, `touchstart`, `touchmove`, and `touchend`. Touch coordinates are extracted using `touch.clientX - rect.left` with `getBoundingClientRect()` for accurate positioning regardless of scroll position. The canvas draws a 2px dark stroke following the pointer/finger movement. A "Clear" button resets the canvas by calling `ctx.clearRect()` and resetting the `hasInk` state.

After each stroke ends (mouseup or touchend), the component calls `canvas.toDataURL("image/png")` and fires `onChange` with the new data URL. The parent component uses this to control whether the submit button is enabled — the submit button requires both `accepted === true` AND `dataUrl` to be non-empty (meaning the user has actually drawn something, not just ticked the checkbox).

I also created `SignatureCredentials.js` — the viewer component that displays the audit trail for a signature record. It fetches `GET /api/signatures` with the appropriate query parameters, then displays the context badge, signer name and email, signed-at time, IP address, user-agent, consent text, document hash, and retention date. For the signature image, it creates a Blob URL from the Drive file fetched via the backend proxy — this prevents the image URL from expiring (as direct Drive share links can).

## Learning Outcomes
- Built `SignaturePad.js` with consent gate, HTML5 Canvas drawing, touch and mouse support
- Understood why the consent checkbox must gate the canvas: satisfies legal "intent to sign" requirement
- Implemented blob URL pattern for Drive image display: `URL.createObjectURL(blob)` with cleanup on unmount
- Designed `SignatureCredentials.js` as a read-only audit viewer with no delete/modify options

## Challenges & Solutions
Touch events on mobile browsers don't automatically prevent page scrolling — `touchmove` caused the page to scroll while drawing. Adding `e.preventDefault()` in the `touchmove` handler (which requires a non-passive event listener: `{ passive: false }`) fixed this.

