Today I integrated the e-signature feature into the three existing capture points: candidate application, onboarding offer letter, and onboarding policy sign-off. For the candidate application in `jobOpeningController.js`, I added a call to `recordSignature()` after `CandidateApplicationModel.create()`. The signature data URL is sent by the frontend along with the application form as a multipart field. The service reuses the already-uploaded signature file ID (`existingDriveFileId`) rather than uploading twice.

For the onboarding offer letter acceptance in `OfferLetterResponse.js` (frontend), I added `SignaturePad` above the acknowledgement checkboxes. The `sig.dataUrl` and `sig.consentText` are included in the POST body. In the corresponding `respondPublicOfferLetter` handler, after saving the employee update, I added a call to `recordOnboardingSignature()` — a helper function I added to `onboardingController.js` that resolves the employee's Drive folder and calls `recordSignature()` with `context: "onboarding_offer"`. The call is wrapped in try/catch and is non-fatal: a signature service failure does not prevent the offer acceptance from completing.

For the policy sign-off form (`DocumentSignForm.js` frontend), I added `SignaturePad` on the last page of the multi-document carousel. The signature only appears when the user has checked all document acknowledgement boxes and is on the final document. The `submitPublicSignDocs` backend handler then calls `recordOnboardingSignature()` with `context: "onboarding_policy"`.

I integrated `SignatureCredentials` into `TalentPool.js` (shows application signature for candidates) and `EmployeeDetail.js` (shows onboarding signatures in the Documents tab). The Documents tab now has a section labeled "E-signatures (onboarding / offboarding)" that shows all signature records for the employee.

## Learning Outcomes
