**Date:** Wednesday, 01 July 2026
**Organization:** Saeculum Solutions
**Project:** Stasis HRMS
**Intern Name:** ___________
**Supervisor:** ___________

## Work Done

Today I studied the Electron tracker agent codebase — `hrms-tracker-agent` — in depth. The agent is built with Electron 31 and uses CommonJS modules (unlike the backend's ES Modules). I read `src/main.js` which is the Electron entry point. Key behaviors: it uses `app.requestSingleInstanceLock()` to ensure only one instance runs — a second launch (from Start Menu or double-click) sends a signal to the already-running instance to open the admin panel instead of starting a second process. After enrollment, the app runs with no visible window, appearing only in the system tray.

I studied the autostart and watchdog mechanism. On Windows, autostart uses `app.setLoginItemSettings({ openAtLogin: true, openAsHidden: true })` to add a registry entry for launching at login. The watchdog is a Windows Task Scheduler task created programmatically using `schtasks` via `child_process.execFile` — it runs every 5 minutes and attempts to launch the agent. Since the single-instance lock makes a relaunch a no-op when the agent is alive, this only has an effect when the agent was killed or crashed. This "resurrect on crash" design ensures the monitoring is always-on.

I read `src/agent.js` — the core runtime loop. Every second, a `tick()` function classifies the elapsed second as active or idle by checking `Date.now() - input.getLastInputAt() > idleThresholdSec * 1000`. After each `sampleWindowSec` seconds (default 60), `flushWindow()` builds a sample object with the accumulated stats (activeSec, idleSec, keyCount, clickCount, mouseDistance, topApps, topSites, sessionEvents) and adds it to an in-memory buffer. Every `uploadFrequencySec` seconds, the buffer is drained to the backend via `api.ingestSamples()`.

I also read `src/store.js` which uses `better-sqlite3` as an offline buffer. If the backend is unreachable, samples are written to a local SQLite database. When connectivity resumes, buffered samples are uploaded in batches. This ensures no activity data is lost during network outages.

## Learning Outcomes
- Understood the Electron single-instance lock and second-instance → admin panel redirect
- Learned the Windows watchdog pattern using Task Scheduler via `schtasks` for always-on monitoring
- Understood the `tick()` → `flushWindow()` → ingest pipeline in `agent.js`
- Learned the SQLite offline buffer pattern: write locally when offline, drain when connectivity resumes

## Challenges & Solutions
Understanding the `powerSaveBlocker` usage in `main.js` required reading the Electron docs. On macOS, app napping can freeze background apps — the `prevent-app-suspension` blocker prevents this so heartbeats keep firing even with no visible window.

