**Date:** Friday, 03 July 2026
**Organization:** Saeculum Solutions
**Project:** Stasis HRMS
**Intern Name:** ___________
**Supervisor:** ___________

## Work Done

On the final day of my internship, I completed the Windows executable build for the tracker agent and conducted a comprehensive review of all the work done over the nine weeks. The build process had a non-obvious challenge: Visual Studio Build Tools 2022 version 17.14 (June 2026) is newer than `@electron/node-gyp`'s version table, causing it to fall back to the `ClangCL` toolset in the generated `.vcxproj` files. Since ClangCL isn't installed, the native module compilation fails with `MSB8020: build tools for ClangCL cannot be found`.

The fix required patching `node_modules/@electron/node-gyp/gyp/pylib/gyp/generator/msvs.py`. In the `_GetMsbuildToolsetOfProject` function, after the toolset is resolved, I added a check: `if toolset == "ClangCL": toolset = "v143"`. The MSVC v143 toolset (VS 2022) correctly builds both `uiohook-napi` and `better-sqlite3` as N-API modules. This patch lives in `node_modules` and is wiped by every `npm install`, so it must be reapplied after reinstalls. I documented this in the `MEMORY.md` project memory for future reference.

The second build blocker was `electron-builder`'s `winCodeSign` bundle — it contains macOS dylib symlinks that require `SeCreateSymbolicLinkPrivilege` to extract on Windows. Enabling Developer Mode in Windows Settings (Settings → System → For developers) grants this privilege to regular users without needing administrator elevation. With both fixes applied, `npm run dist:win` completed successfully and produced `dist/StasisMonitor-Setup-0.1.0.exe` — a fully packaged NSIS installer for Stasis Monitor.

I spent the final hours writing a comprehensive handover document for my supervisor, summarizing all the features implemented during the internship: the e-signature system, the WYSIWYG email builder, the leave balance inline editing grid, the frontend palette unification, and the Electron tracker agent Windows build. I also documented the two tracker agent build workarounds clearly so future developers can reproduce the build without encountering the same blockers.

Reflecting on the nine weeks, I went from zero knowledge of the project to being able to independently implement full-stack features spanning backend Mongoose models, Express controller handlers, React frontend components, and Electron native modules. The most valuable learning was the discipline of reading existing code patterns before writing new code — every feature in Stasis HRMS follows consistent patterns that, once understood, make new feature development much faster and less error-prone.

## Learning Outcomes
- Successfully built `StasisMonitor-Setup-0.1.0.exe` using electron-builder with NSIS
- Learned the node-gyp ClangCL → v143 patch for VS Build Tools 2022 17.14 compatibility
- Understood the Windows Developer Mode requirement for electron-builder symlink extraction
- Completed a comprehensive nine-week internship across all modules of a production-grade HRMS

## Challenges & Solutions
The ClangCL toolset fallback was the most cryptic error of the entire internship — the error message pointed to a missing toolset but gave no hint that it was caused by a version table mismatch in the gyp generator. Tracing the error to `msvs.py` required reading the node-gyp source code directly.

